iolo@mist.demon.co.uk (Iolo Davidson) writes:

> In article <strnlghtCpBLsn.A67@netcom.com>
>            david@sternlight.com "David Sternlight" writes:
> 
> > Unfortunately, with his assumptions it takes just under 4 months to break a
> > 1024 bit key, and another expert message recently posted has such keys
> > lasting for 20 to 40 years.
> 
> At 30 million pounds per solution, I wonder how many mischievous 
> postings it will take to bankrupt the NSA, or the US government (already 
> insolvent by all accounts).  
> 
> The moral of the above is: if you want your 1024 bit key to be safe, use 
> it a lot.  Use a bunch of different ones.  Encrypt everything.  If you 
> haven't anything important to send, send each other encrypted nonsense, 
> preferably by anonymous server.  Let's have a little hubba hubba out 
> there.  
> 
> The more noise there is, the more time and equipment will be wasted on 
> reading junk, and the less sense key cracking will make in dollar terms.  
> The laws of economics may yet be more effective than the constitution.
 
That's how the DoD's AUTODIN used to work - maybe still does for
all I know. Not only was all traffic encrypted no matter how
trivial, but between messages terminal spewed out encrypted
gibberish. Any enemy, before attempting to decipher a message,
had to find it in all the "noise.'


